Introduction to R - Exercises

Candace Savonen

2020

The goal of these exercises is to help you get comfortable with using R and R notebooks by continuing to play with the dataset we used in the 01-intro_to_base_R notebook and 02-intro_to_ggplot2 notebooks.

Objectives

  • Load tidyverse
  • Read in TSV file as a data frame
  • Practice subsetting data frame and exploring data structure
  • Use R functions to manipulate data
  • Save data frame to TSV
  • Create a plot
  • Save plot to a file

Set Up

Use this chunk to load the tidyverse library.

library(tidyverse)

Read in the gene results file

Use readr::read_tsv to read in the file “gene_results_GSE44971.tsv” and assign it the name stats_df.

stats_df <- readr::read_tsv(file.path("data", "gene_results_GSE44971.tsv"))

Use dplyr::filter to keep only the data for the astrocytoma_normal contrast in stats_df.

astrocytoma_normal_df <- dplyr::filter(stats_df, contrast == "astrocytoma_normal")

Use the nrow argument on astrocytoma_normal_df to see if your filter worked. You should have 2268 rows.

nrow(astrocytoma_normal_df)
[1] 2268

Do the same filtering as you did above, but this time, use a %>% by removing stats_df from the first argument position and piping it into the filter.

astrocytoma_normal_df <- stats_df %>% 
  dplyr::filter(contrast == "astrocytoma_normal")

Save your filtered data to a TSV file using readr::write_tsv. Call it astrocytoma_normal_contrast_results.tsv and save it to the results directory.

readr::write_tsv(astrocytoma_normal_df,
                 file.path("results", "astrocytoma_normal_contrast_results.tsv"))

Create a density plot

Set up a ggplot object for astrocytoma_normal_df and set x as the average expression variable. Use the + to add on a layer called geom_density()

ggplot(astrocytoma_normal_df, aes(x = avg_expression)) + 
  geom_density()

Use the plot you started above and add a ggtheme layer to play with its aesthetics (e.g. theme_classic()) See the ggthemes vignette to see a list of ggtheme options.

ggplot(astrocytoma_normal_df, aes(x = avg_expression)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  theme_minimal()

Feel free to make other customizations to this plot by adding more layers with +. You could add a ylab() and xlab() and/or by getting inspiration from this handy cheatsheet for ggplot2.

# Customize your plot!
ggplot(astrocytoma_normal_df, aes(x = avg_expression)) + 
  geom_density(fill = "lightgreen") + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  xlab("Average Expression") +
  ylab("Density") + 
  ggtitle("Average Expression Density for Astrocytoma - Normal")

Save your plot as a PNG.

ggsave(
  plot = last_plot(), # This will retrieve the last plot you printed. 
  filename = file.path("plots", "average_expression_density_plot.png")
)
